## Program Overview
## Explain what your program does.
The program is a Java application that creates a 9x9 Sudoku board and turns it into a game. First, it generates a correct Sudoku solution where every row, column, and 3x3 box has the numbers 1 through 9 with no repeats. After that, it removes some numbers to make a puzzle. The user can then try to solve it by entering a row, column, and number. The program checks if the answer is correct and keeps going until the puzzle is finished or the user quits.


## Data Structures
 Explain how you used:
 a. the 2D array
I used a 2D array int[][] board to store the Sudoku board. Since Sudoku is basically a grid, the 2D array makes it easy to keep track of rows and columns. Each position in the array represents one square on the board.

 b. the array and/or ArrayList
I used a simple way to generate the first row of numbers 1 through 9 with a loop. I also used another 2D array called solution to store a copy of the completed board so that the program checks the user’s answers later.

Algorithm Design
 Explain how your program generates a solved Sudoku board.
 Describe the pattern, logic, or method you used.


To generate the solved board, I used a shifting pattern. First, I filled the first row with the numbers 1 through 9 in order. Then, for each row, I copied the previous row and shifted the numbers to the left. Most rows are shifted by 3 positions, but every third row is shifted by 1 position instead. This pattern makes sure that all rows, columns and 3x3 subgrids contain different numbers from 1 to 9 b/c of this pattern, the board automatically meets all the rules. After making the solved board, I created the puzzle by randomly putting positions in the grid and replacing them with 0 which is the blank space. The user then fills in these blanks during the game.

Methods
 List and explain the purpose of each method.
fillBoard() creates the Sudoku board and fills the first row and then builds the rest by copying and shifting rows. 
copyBoard() makes a copy of the completed board and is used to keep track the correct answers so we can check the user’s guesses.
removeNumbers() randomly removes numbers from the board to create the puzzle.
playGame() shows the board, and asks the user for input and checks if the answer is correct, and updates the and updates the board.
isComplete() checks if the board is finished by seeing if there are any 0s left.
printBoard() prints the board.

